Ken Miller is a curator, writer-editor and creative director. He has presented exhibitions in the United States, Europe and Asia, often with private sponsorship, and has published three books of art, fashion and photography. He writes regularly for several publications, including contributing a recurring multimedia feature to ''T: The New York Times Style Magazine''. 
  
== Works as editor==
In 1999-2000, Ken Miller was editor in chief for the New York office of [[Modo (Wireless device)|modo]], a wireless handheld guide to culture and nightlife from Scout Electromedia.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Green|first1=Penelope|title=Mirror, Mirror: A Life Coach to Hold in Your Hand|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/24/style/mirror-mirror-a-life-coach-to-hold-in-your-hand.html|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> Design for modo was provided by [[IDEO]] with an advertising campaign by [[Wieden+Kennedy]]. 

From 2001-2007, Miller was editor of ''[[Tokion]]'' magazine, a youth-culture oriented design, arts and style magazine. ''Tokion'' published two separate editions in English and Japanese, with distribution in North America, Europe and Japan.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Tsunami of Japanese Pop Culture|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2004-07-25/online-extra-a-tsunami-of-japanese-pop-culture|website=BusinessWeek|accessdate=July 25, 2004}}</ref> As editor, Miller conducted numerous interviews with artists including [[Yoko Ono]], [[Maurizio Cattelan]], [[Mike Kelley (artist)|Mike Kelley]], [[Yayoi Kusama]], [[Ed Ruscha]] and [[Jeff Koons]]; musicians including [[Lou Reed]], [[Iggy Pop]], [[Timbaland]], [[Bj<U+00F6>rk]] and [[Thurston Moore]]; filmmakers including [[Gus Van Sant]], [[Michel Gondry]], [[Harmony Korine]], [[Miranda July]] and [[Judd Apatow]]; actors [[Samantha Morton]], [[Chlo<U+00EB> Sevigny|Chlo<U+00EB> Sevigny]] and [[Isabelle Huppert]]; chef [[Nobu Matsuhisa]]; basketball player [[Yao Ming]]; and stuntman [[Evel Knievel]]. 

In 2008, Miller was editor of ''Revisionaries, A Decade of Art in Tokion''<ref>{{cite book|title=Revisionaries|date=2008|publisher=Abrams Image|isbn=0-8109-9437-2}}</ref>, published with Abrams Image. ''Revisionaries'' compiled art and interviews from nearly 100 artists who had contributed to the magazine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Revisionaries: A Decade of Art in Tokion|url=http://www.powells.com/biblio/9780810994379|website=Powell's}}</ref>

Miller is author-editor of ''SHOOT: Photography of the Moment''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Miller|first1=Ken|title=SHOOT|date=2009|publisher=Rizzoli|isbn=0847831930}}</ref>, a fashion and fine art <U+2018>[[Snapshot aesthetic|snapshot]]<U+2019> photography compilation published in 2009 with Rizzoli.<ref>{{cite web|title=SHOOT|url=http://books.google.com/books/about/Shoot.html?id=C9dLAQAAIAAJ|website=Google Books}}</ref> ''SHOOT'' was supported with events and exhibitions at the [[New Museum]] in New York<ref>{{cite web|title=SHOOT Captures Photography of Modern Times|url=http://www.papermag.com/2009/09/shoot_captures_photography_of_1.php|publisher=Paper Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In the Heat of the Moment|url=https://www.nowness.com/story/the-heat-of-the-moment|website=Nowness}}</ref>, [[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive|Berkeley Art Museum]]<ref>{{cite web|title=L@te at BAMPFA|url=http://www.bampfa.berkeley.edu/exhibition/late111309|website=BAM/PFA}}</ref>, [[Tate Modern]] in London<ref>{{cite web|title=Shoot 'Em Up|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/photography/article/5457/1/shoot-em-up|website=Dazed Digital|publisher=Dazed and Confused}}</ref>, Colette in Paris, [[Foam Fotografiemuseum Amsterdam|FOAM Fotografiemuseum]] in Amsterdam, [[Ullens Center for Contemporary Art|UCCA]] in Beijing, and [[Parco (retailer)|PARCO]] in Tokyo, with additional events and exhibitions in Barcelona, Berlin, Dublin, and Mexico City.

In 2009-2010, Miller was editor of two issues of ''Spread Artculture''<ref>{{cite web|title=SPREAD ArtCulture|url=http://issuu.com/spreadartculture/docs/2009|website=ISSUU}}</ref> magazine with cover profiles of [[Pharrell Williams]] and [[M.I.A. (rapper)|M.I.A.]] 

In 2012, Miller was an editor of ''Opening Ceremony''<ref>{{cite book|title=Opening Ceremony|date=2012|publisher=Rizzoli|isbn=978-0-8478-3870-7}}</ref>, a monograph on the fashion brand and retailer, published in 2012 with Rizzoli. Julie Schumacher and Rory Satran were also editors of the book, with Opening Ceremony<U+2019>s founders Carol Lim and Humberto Leon as authors and additional contributions from [[Spike Jonze]] and [[Chlo<U+00EB> Sevigny]]. ''Opening Ceremony'' chronicled the first 10 years of the store<U+2019>s history through advertising imagery, private snapshots, quotes and anecdotes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lipke|first1=David|title=Opening Ceremony Reflects on 10 Years|url=http://www.wwd.com/eye/fashion/opening-ceremony-reflects-on-10-years-6170462|publisher=WWD}}</ref>
== Works as writer==
Since 2013, Ken has been a writer for [[T: The New York Times Style Magazine]], contributing <U+2018>Under the Influence', a recurring multimedia feature that profiles artists, musicians and designers such as [[Kara Walker]], [[Kim Gordon]] and [[Alex Katz]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Under the Influence|url=http://query.nytimes.com/search/sitesearch/?vertical=tmagazine/#/under+the+influence/since1851/allresults/1/byKen+Miller/relevance/tmagazine/|website=T: The New York Times Style Magazine|publisher=T: The New York Times Style Magazine}}</ref> He has additionally written for ''[[New York Magazine]]'', ''[[W (magazine)|W]]'', ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'', ''[[V (magazine)|V]]'', ''[[Details (magazine)|Details]]'', ''[[Purple (magazine)|Purple]]'' and Business of Fashion. He has written travel books for [[Rough Guides]] and contributed travel writing to [[National Public Radio]].

==Curator==
In 2003, ''Tokion'' founded Creativity Now, an annual arts and media conference in New York and Tokyo. Speakers at the conference were drawn from a variety of creative disciplines, and included musicians [[Brian Eno]], [[Kim Gordon]] and [[Antony Hegarty|Anthony Hegarty]]; fashion designers [[Proenza Schouler]]; artists [[Matthew Barney]], [[Tom Sachs (artist)|Tom Sachs]], [[Doug Aitken]] and [[Raymond Pettibon]]; directors [[Lynne Ramsay]], [[Mike Mills (director)|Mike Mills]], [[Gaspar No<U+00E9>]], [[Neil LaBute]] and [[John Cameron Mitchell]]; and graphic designer [[Peter Saville (graphic designer)|Peter Saville]]. Creativity Now was presented from 2003-2006 and in 2008 the conference won ''AdAge'''s Vanguard Award.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dumenco|first1=Simon|title=The American Magazine Vanguard Awards|url=http://adage.com/article/the-media-guy/american-magazine-vanguard-awards/131470/|publisher=AdAge}}</ref>

For Fall 2008 New York Fashion Week, Miller curated a series of conversations on art, music, fashion, health and design for [[MINI Cooper]] cars.<ref>{{cite web|title=MINI's Creative Use of Space|url=https://www.minispace.com/en_us/ Creative Use of Space|website=MINI Space}}</ref> In 2009, Miller was consulting curator for a 'Saturdays at Phillips'<ref>{{cite web|title=Urban Art Adds Ultracool Edge to Apr 25 Phillips de Pury Sale|url=http://www.auctioncentralnews.com/index.php/auctions/upcoming-auctions/809-urban-art-adds-ultracool-edge-to-apr-25-phillips-de-pury-sale|website=Auction Central News}}</ref> auction of young artists by the [[Phillips de Pury]] auction house.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Panousopoulos|first1=Spyridon|title=Redefining Urban Art at The Auction House|url=http://flavorwire.com/18899/exclusive-redefining-urban-art-at-the-auction-house|website=Flavorwire|accessdate=April 23, 2009}}</ref>

In 2010, Miller curated a <U+2018>UT<U+2019> shirt series featuring black and white photography for apparel brand [[Uniqlo]]; the shirts featured contributions from [[Lee Friedlander|Lee Friedander]] and [[Daid<U+014D> Moriyama]], among others, and were sold in Uniqlo stores worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Browne|first1=Alix|title=Art on Your Sleeve|url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/24/art-on-your-sleeve/|website=T: The New York Times Style Magazine|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Uniqlo Shoots for the Basic|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/fashion/uniqlo-ken-miller|website=Interview magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fischer|first1=David|title=Uniqlo UT Series "A Function of Forms"|url=http://www.selectism.com/2010/06/28/uniqlo-ut-series-a-function-of-forms-t-shirts-for-july/|website=Selectism|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Weinstein|first1=Greg|title='A Function of Forms' Collection by Ken Miller|url=http://slamxhype.com/style/a-function-of-forms-collection-by-ken-miller/|website=Slam X Hype|accessdate=July 8, 2010}}</ref> In 2011, he curated fashion week photos and videos for Milk Studios, in New York with support from [[Leica Camera|Leica]] cameras and Vimeo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Commissions|url=http://www.milkmade.com/commissions|website=Milk Made}}</ref>

In 2012-2013, Miller was curator for Fujifilm<U+2019>s [[Fujifilm X-series|X-Series]] cameras. Photographers [[William Eggleston]], [[Stephen Shore]], [[Nan Goldin]], [[Terry Richardson]], [[Ryan McGinley]] and [[Martin Parr]] were commissioned to shoot original photos using the cameras.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Storm|first1=Christian|title=The Roster for Ken Miller's 'Photography' Show Will Blow Your Mind|url=http://www.vice.com/read/ken-miller-photography-exhibit|publisher=Vice}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=LaBarre|first1=Suzanne|title=New Work From Photography's Greats, All Shot on the Same Camera|url=http://www.fastcodesign.com/1671762/new-work-from-photography-s-greats-all-shot-on-the-same-camera|publisher=Fast Company|accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref> The resulting photographs were presented at exhibitions in New York at the [[Aperture Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Photography exhibition|url=http://www.aperture.org/exhibition/photography/|publisher=Aperture Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aperture's 'Photography'  Exhibition Combines Big Names, Punchy Colors...|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/03/apertures-photography-exhibition-_n_2592532.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=February 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Photography at Aperture Gallery|url=http://museemagazine.com/culture/art-out/photography-at-aperture-gallery/|publisher=Musee Magazine|accessdate=February 6, 2013}}</ref>, Tokyo (at Omotesando Hills), Milan (at Galleria Carla Sozzani).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stella|first1=Marta|title=Photography: da Richardson a McGinley la nuova mostra alla Galleria Carla Sozzani|url=http://www.marieclaire.it/Attualita/news-appuntamenti/Photography-New-Works-mostra-Richardson-McGinley-Galleria-Carla-Sozzani-Milano|publisher=Marie Claire|accessdate=October 31, 2012}}</ref> and Seoul (at Hyundai Card Design Library). 

In 2014, Ken curated two exhibitions at the Sundance Film Festival. 1MSQFT showcased music and design as part of a cultural programming series for Microsoft; SPACE, with sponsorship by Patagonia, presented landscapes by prominent fine art and fashion photographers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Graver|first1=David|title=Sundance 2014: SPACE and 1MSQFT|url=http://www.coolhunting.com/culture/sundance-space-and-1msqft.php|website=Coolhunting|accessdate=January 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Carr-Harris|first1=Dory|title=How Sundance Is Generating a New Creative Culture|url=http://www.psfk.com/2014/01/sundance-festival-creativity-1msqft.html|website=PSFK|accessdate=January 27, 2014}}</ref> Photographers exhibited in SPACE included [[Juergen Teller]], [[Jack Pierson]], Lee Friedlander, Nan Goldin, [[Catherine Opie]], [[Todd Hido]] and [[Mike Brodie]].

